				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$R = \frac{{1 - r\cos \left( {2\pi f_{m} /F} \right)}}{{1 + r\cos \left( {2\pi f_{m} /F} \right)}}$$\end{document}where F is the free spectral range of the comb filter and the fm is the instantaneous frequency of the microwave signal. Now, based on measurement of the optical mixing unit, a mixer is created between optically modulated signal and the microwave signal with a time delay, which gives a shifted version of output power. A microwave signal is correspondingly split into two halves and feed to the MZM. Then, the IFM is calculated by the detection by PD. To increase the frequency measurement range, a small delay can be added to the optical link to get rid of the distortion in the coaxial cable. Another method of measurement based on dispersive element used the dispersive delay to familiarize the microwave power fading for designing photonic-based microwave filter. As both are frequency-dependent, the IFM can be done by the microwave power detection [107]. To make the IFM independent of microwave power, more than two power ratios are needed to be derived. If two powers can be detected by two channels, the ratio will be16R=P1P2=R1cos2πx1λ1fm2c+αR2cos2πx2λ2fm2c+β\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
