				\begin{document}$$R_{{{\text{res}}}} = \frac{C}{2B}$$\end{document}where C is the velocity of light traveling in free space, B is the bandwidth of the waveform. A microwave signal bandwidth of 1.5 GHz can give a resolution of 0.1 m in synthetic aperture radar (SAR) [117]. For a wide range of high-frequency bandwidth (suppose tens of GHz), transmitting, receiving and processing is impossible to be done in single electronic circuits. Even RF front end-based antenna does not give good outcomes. So, this generation got the photonics system to overcome all these situations with multi-function and multiband integration. Usually, for microwave radar measurements, electronics devices have very good resolution and suppleness is used. Nevertheless, high-speed, high-bandwidth microwave signal measurement will always need modern photonics science. [118]. Photonics-based technique converts the broad band microwave signals to optical signals, which can drastically compress hundreds of terahertz frequency in optical domain. So, by using low power consumption and low cost optical devices, we can easily eliminate this problem. After all the processing and measurement, the electrical up-conversion is very easily done by optoelectrical oscillators. The flow of the microwave parameter measurement is like this, first, the microwave signal is converted into optical signal by electro-optic (EO) modulator then optical signal processing module measures all the parameters and converts them into amplitude function, after this a photodetector pulls out these data [119].

This technology uses laser light to measure the elevation of things like the ground, forest, and buildings etc. As the sonar uses sound waves for mapping things and radar uses radio waves, similarly lidar uses the light. There are three ways to collect data from lidar systems, like from ground, from airplane even from space satellites. The airborne lidar system is the most commonly used lidar system for collecting data. Now, we need to understand the four parts in the airborne LiDAR system. The first one is, the laser light from the transmitter scans the earth from above as the plane flies [139]. In the laser the ultraviolet range, visible range and the near-infrared range. The next one is, for finding latitude, longitude and altitude it needs GPS system, which allows to figure out where are the lidar reflection is on the ground. The third one is inertial measurement unit (IMU). This IMU tracks the tilt of the plane in the sky as it flies in the sky, which is important for accurate elevation calculations. And the last one is data accusation system and a computer which helps to store or record the data collected by the lidar. The principle of lidar data collection is as follows. First, the laser of the lidar system scans the earth by actively emitting light energy toward the ground. A burst of light energy is admitted from the lidar system, which is known as pulse, and the reflected light energy what to be recorded is known as return. To get the altitude, lidar measures the time that takes for a light energy to travel to the ground and back. Suppose the total travel time is T and speed of light is c, the multiplication we have to divide by 2 since the light traveled to the ground and back.20Distance=T∗c2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\text{Distance}} = \frac{T*c}{2}$$\end{document}
